    <!-- PROSE BLOCK 3: Why One Compounds + Economics -->
    <div class="prose prose-lg text-body max-w-none space-y-6 leading-relaxed">

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mt-10 mb-4">Why One Compounds and the Other Decays</h2>
      <p>
        A paid link on a guest-post marketplace has a deindexing problem. The publisher's incentive is the fee, not your content. The site exists to sell placements.
      </p>
      <p>
        Google has been deindexing marketplace sites in waves since <a class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2" href="https://developers.google.com/search/blog/2022/08/helpful-content-update" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">the Helpful Content Update</a> rolled out in 2022. When a marketplace domain gets deindexed, every paid link on it disappears from the index overnight. The money is gone. The signal is gone.
      </p>
      <p>
        Indexation is the threshold every retrieval system relies on. AI systems cite what retrieval can see. Deindexed content is invisible to Google, to Bing, and to the corpora ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Gemini retrieve from. Paid links sit on exactly the kind of content that fails this threshold systematically.
      </p>
      <p>
        An earned link on an established publication does not face this problem. Major publications, trade pubs, analyst sites, and authoritative vendor properties do not get deindexed. They are the domains retrieval systems are tuned to trust.
      </p>
      <p>
        The citation becomes part of the permanent record of the category. When a new AI system is trained or a new retrieval index is built, the mention is part of the corpus.
      </p>
      <p>
        It compounds. Each additional mention adds to a pattern AI systems read as: this brand is recognised in this category.
      </p>
      <p class="font-semibold text-ink">The economics are inverted:</p>
      <p>
        A <strong>$437 paid link</strong> sits on a marketplace site built to sell placements. When that site gets deindexed — and Google has been deindexing them in waves since 2022 — the investment goes to zero overnight. The money is gone. The signal is gone.
      </p>
      <p>
        A <strong>$437 earned mention</strong> on an authoritative site has no deindex risk. It compounds. Each additional mention adds to the pattern AI systems read as: this brand belongs in this category.
      </p>
      <p>
        Same upfront cost. Opposite trajectories.
      </p>

    </div>

    <!-- VISUAL 3: Economics comparison -->
    <div class="my-10 w-full max-w-2xl mx-auto grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
