      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mt-10 mb-4">What This Means for B2B SaaS Marketing Teams</h2>
      <p>
        If your buyer is asking ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, or Google's AI Overviews which tool to use in your category, your brand either shows up or doesn't. Paid links on marketplace sites will not put you in those answers. A pattern of earned mentions across the top publications in your category will.
      </p>
      <p class="font-semibold text-ink">The trajectory is set:</p>
      <p>
        Every B2B SaaS category will converge on this. The only variable is whether you build earned coverage before or after your competitors.
      </p>
      <p>
        The brands accumulating that coverage now are the ones that will be surfaced as the defaults when their categories fully shift to AI-mediated search. That shift has already started.
      </p>
      <p>
        The outcome is commercial, not technical. When your brand is consistently cited and surfaced by AI systems, you enter more buying conversations before your competitors do. Paid links cannot produce that pattern. Earned coverage on authoritative sites is how you build it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Stop buying links on marketplace sites. Redirect the budget into producing the kind of data, commentary, and expert insight that authority publishers want to cover. Earned coverage is slower to produce than a marketplace order. It is also the only output that survives the shift. That is the work Ranking Atlas runs as fixed-price campaigns: editorial placements on authoritative sites, guaranteed per campaign, no retainer.
